<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pennisetum setaceum, </i>crimson fountain grass, has a Cal-IPC rank of Moderate. It is native to northern Africa but is now widely established in the United States, including Arizona, California, Colorado, Hawaii, Florida, Louisiana, and Tennessee. In southern California, it invades grasslands, deserts, canyons, and roadsides (Benton 1998). It is a showy ornamental, perennial bunch grass to 1.5 m tall with lax purplish red, spikelike flowering stalks. It reproduces by either fertilized or apomictic seeds, which remain viable in the soil for at least seven years (DiTomaso and Healy 2007, Lovich 2000). Seeds are primarily wind-dispersed but may disperse long distances from humans, livestock, vehicles, and water. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pennisetum clandestinum, </i>Kikuyu grass, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited. It is a low-growing perennial grass to 50 cm tall with creeping stolons and rhizome. This African native was introduced to the state as an erosion-controlling, ground cover. It occurs on the Central California Coast (261A) and Southern California Coast (261B). <i>P. clandestinum </i>is a federally listed noxious weed (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pennisetum ciliare, </i>buffel grass, is unranked by Cal-IPC. It is spreading throughout the Sonoran Desert and is a threat to hot-desert natives, especially in Arizona. It is native to Africa. It has the rank character of <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>with open stems to 1.5 m tall. Planted as a forage plant in Texas and northern Mexico, <i>P. ciliare </i>grows in the Colorado Desert (322C) and Southern California Coast (261B) in California. References also use the name <i>Cenchrus ciliaris </i>(DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pennisetum villosum </i>is unranked by Cal-IPC. Feathertop is a showy, tufted, perennial grass to 80 cm with white spikelike flower heads. This ornamental is less invasive than other fountain grasses, but it tolerates saline conditions (DiTomaso and Healy 2007).<br/>
<br/>
Previously cited as <i>Pennisetum setaceum </i> Herbaceous Semi-Natural Alliance in the 2009 publication of <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>.  the name has been updated to better fit the alliance description. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
