    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Pennisetum setaceum</i> includes the Central California Coast (261A), Great Valley (262A), Sonoran Desert (322B), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands have colonized roadsides in the western portions of Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and are replacing stands of the <i>Encelia farinosa </i>alliance in some areas.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands in Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) are most prevalent on steep slopes and coastal bluffs close to the ocean. The stands have been seen far from roads and development, suggesting that <i>P. setaceum </i>can colonize unstable slopes far from sources. Stands in coastal and central San Diego Co. are common on steep slopes near the wildland-urban interface; some stands are establishing westward from the San Diego Wild Animal Park, where the <i>Pennisetum </i>spp. are groundcovers. <i>P. setaceum </i>is replacing stands of the <i>Artemisia californica, Coreopsis gigantea, Encelia californica, Eriogonum cinereum, Eriogonum fasciculatum, </i>and <i>Malosma laurina </i>alliances especially following fires.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pennisetum setaceum </i>is a highly aggressive, fire-adapted colonizer that readily replaces native plants and rapidly reestablishes after burning. In Hawaii and southern California, it alters the natural fire regime and is a major threat to some critically imperiled plant species and natural vegetation. Like other nonnative grasses, <i>P. setaceum </i>raises fuel loads and increases the probability and spread of fire adjacent to human habitation, which may result in damage to native vegetation adapted to less often and extreme fire regimes. The long-lived seeds make its control extremely difficult. Small infestations are controlled by hand-uprooting the plants and destroying the inflorescences in order to prevent seed dispersal; several treatments are required. Extensive infestations are controlled best with the help of herbicides (Lovich 2000, Benton 2006, DiTomaso and Healy 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

